should achieve scaling?

00:05:16.810 --> 00:05:20.620
And specifically, how would
that differ for a startup,

00:05:20.620 --> 00:05:24.030
as you mentioned, versus,
let's say a large organization

00:05:24.030 --> 00:05:26.590
like Google?

00:05:26.590 --> 00:05:29.080
HUGGY RAO: Let me take
a quick stab at that.

00:05:29.080 --> 00:05:34.790
For a startup, I think
the advice that both of us

00:05:34.790 --> 00:05:38.180
talk about in the
book is, smart scaling

00:05:38.180 --> 00:05:41.430
means that you take time,
and you do it slowly.

00:05:41.430 --> 00:05:45.330
We just recently
had an organization

00:05:45.330 --> 00:05:50.210
that actually was
acquired by Google, Waze.

00:05:50.210 --> 00:05:52.360
And we actually had
one of their executives

00:05:52.360 --> 00:05:55.000
come and talk to our class,
and he gave a great example.

00:05:55.000 --> 00:05:56.860
They were growing in Israel.

00:05:56.860 --> 00:06:00.560
You've got all these resources,
and the VC is saying,

00:06:00.560 --> 00:06:03.750
now's the time to expand
higher, higher, higher.

00:06:03.750 --> 00:06:07.180
The top managers get
together and say, you know,

00:06:07.180 --> 00:06:09.670
now is the time to
have a hiring freeze.

00:06:09.670 --> 00:06:11.820
And that's sort of
somewhat counterintuitive.

00:06:11.820 --> 00:06:14.500
And people within the company
are astonished, how could you

00:06:14.500 --> 00:06:16.780
say you have a hiring
freeze right when you've

00:06:16.780 --> 00:06:18.980
got all this money from the VCs?

00:06:18.980 --> 00:06:22.620
And the argument
was the following.

00:06:22.620 --> 00:06:24.830
The moment you
expand, you actually

00:06:24.830 --> 00:06:28.240
are going to get a lot of smart
people with very many ideas.

00:06:28.240 --> 00:06:31.920
And since you want to focus on a
particular product application,

00:06:31.920 --> 00:06:34.330
you're going to wind up
spending a lot of time

00:06:34.330 --> 00:06:37.040
saying no to their smart ideas.

00:06:37.040 --> 00:06:38.960
And that's not something
you want to do.

00:06:38.960 --> 00:06:41.250
The other interesting
thing was, when

00:06:41.250 --> 00:06:44.390
you hire people in a
startup, the smart people

00:06:44.390 --> 00:06:46.820
assume they can hit
the ground running.

00:06:46.820 --> 00:06:48.790
But often many of them can't.

00:06:48.790 --> 00:06:50.850
And very quickly you've
shifted the ratio

00:06:50.850 --> 00:06:53.360
of unproductive to
productive people, at least

00:06:53.360 --> 00:06:55.117
for a short window of time.

00:06:55.117 --> 00:06:56.700
And the third thing
is, of course, you

00:06:56.700 --> 00:06:59.890
increase coordination
costs enormously.

00:06:59.890 --> 00:07:01.920
So what they did was--
they did a smart thing--

00:07:01.920 --> 00:07:04.030
which is hiring freeze.

00:07:04.030 --> 00:07:07.010
But they made sure,
during that period,

00:07:07.010 --> 00:07:09.080
every single
employee was focused

00:07:09.080 --> 00:07:13.410
on one number-- improving
their retention of users

00:07:13.410 --> 00:07:14.750
after three months.

00:07:14.750 --> 00:07:18.800
And pretty much every day,
you have one question to ask.

00:07:18.800 --> 00:07:21.270
What did I do today to
improve that number?

00:07:21.270 --> 00:07:23.970
So scaling smartly,
very important

00:07:23.970 --> 00:07:25.530
for small organizations.

00:07:25.530 --> 00:07:26.940
I'll turn it over to you for
the larger organizations--

00:07:26.940 --> 00:07:27.950
BOB SUTTON: --I
get the large end?

00:07:27.950 --> 00:07:29.810
Well, I would also
emphasize that there's

00:07:29.810 --> 00:07:32.080
a lot of things
that are similar.

00:07:32.080 --> 00:07:35.290
And in particular, there's
kind of two principles that

00:07:35.290 --> 00:07:36.910
are implied in what Huggy said.

00:07:36.910 --> 00:07:39.900
One is the notion that
adding more people

00:07:39.900 --> 00:07:40.980
isn't necessarily good.

00:07:40.980 --> 00:07:43.500
This notion that many
hands make light work.

00:07:43.500 --> 00:07:46.080
And we were actually
talking about this at lunch.

00:07:46.080 --> 00:07:49.990
So in 2002, one of my other
co-authors, Jeff Pfeffer and I

00:07:49.990 --> 00:07:52.910
interviewed Larry Page, when
Google was about 400 people.

00:07:52.910 --> 00:07:55.740
And Larry emphasized how
the venture capitalists

00:07:55.740 --> 00:07:58.324
were giving all this grief that
he wasn't hiring fast enough.

00:07:58.324 --> 00:08:00.990
And that all of his friends from
Stanford were giving him grief.

00:08:00.990 --> 00:08:05.230
But he said, we really have
to slow down, and hire and get

00:08:05.230 --> 00:08:07.670
the right people who
can grow with Google.

00:08:07.670 --> 00:08:10.020
And I'm not going
to back off on that.

00:08:10.020 --> 00:08:12.360
And then, for the book, we
interviewed Shona Brown,

00:08:12.360 --> 00:08:14.420
who was quite senior
here for many years

00:08:14.420 --> 00:08:16.410
and helped grow sort
of the non-product part

00:08:16.410 --> 00:08:18.210
of the organization,
in particular.

00:08:18.210 --> 00:08:22.140
And Shona said, we
constantly had this issue,

00:08:22.140 --> 00:08:23.970
where people are telling
us to hire faster,

00:08:23.970 --> 00:08:26.790
but we had to make sure we got
the right people in the seats.

00:08:26.790 --> 00:08:29.503
And I think that's a pretty
good philosophy, , see,

00:08:29.503 --> 00:08:32.390
even the small versus
a large company.

00:08:32.390 --> 00:08:35.100
But if I was going to talk
about large companies,

00:08:35.100 --> 00:08:37.570
one of things that becomes
increasingly important as they

00:08:37.570 --> 00:08:41.330
grow larger is-- and this
is Huggy's expression--

00:08:41.330 --> 00:08:44.250
is the notion that bad
is stronger than good.

00:08:44.250 --> 00:08:47.380
Or the path to greatness
is to get rid of badness,

00:08:47.380 --> 00:08:48.870
so bad to great.

00:08:48.870 --> 00:08:52.210
And so what happens as
companies get older,

00:08:52.210 --> 00:08:55.820
very often sort of bad
behavior or ineffectiveness

00:08:55.820 --> 00:08:56.990
starts growing and growing.

00:08:56.990 --> 00:09:00.240
And if you just push the
good, and you don't get rid

00:09:00.240 --> 00:09:01.822
of the bad, the
bad gets obscured.

00:09:01.822 --> 00:09:03.530
And there's lots of
evidence that, things

00:09:03.530 --> 00:09:07.460
like laziness, incompetence,
all sorts of difficult things,

00:09:07.460 --> 00:09:09.100
just overwhelm the goodness.

00:09:09.100 --> 00:09:11.980
So good companies, and
I'll sort of stop here,

00:09:11.980 --> 00:09:16.190
they view scaling as a
problem of more or less.

00:09:16.190 --> 00:09:18.200
They're always
adding more people,

00:09:18.200 --> 00:09:20.635
expanding the more
places and so on.

00:09:20.635 --> 00:09:22.260
But in the process,
they're getting rid

00:09:22.260 --> 00:09:24.010
of things that are
getting in the way, are

00:09:24.010 --> 00:09:26.160
no longer effective.

00:09:26.160 --> 00:09:29.200
HUGGY RAO: If I could just
add one more line to that.

00:09:29.200 --> 00:09:32.270
The big difference, I would say,
between a small company scaling

00:09:32.270 --> 00:09:35.520
and a large company scaling
is that, in a large company,

00:09:35.520 --> 00:09:39.730
I would hypothesize that
the larger the company,

00:09:39.730 --> 00:09:43.020
the greater the probability
that the smart people inside

00:09:43.020 --> 00:09:45.920
are going to become dumber.

00:09:45.920 --> 00:09:47.554
What I mean by that
is, obviously I

00:09:47.554 --> 00:09:48.470
don't mean to insist--

00:09:48.470 --> 00:09:49.678
BOB SUTTON: Take that Google.

00:09:49.678 --> 00:09:50.602
[LAUGHTER]

00:09:50.602 --> 00:09:52.060
HUGGY RAO: --I
don't mean to insist

00:09:52.060 --> 00:09:54.170
that smart people become stupid.

00:09:54.170 --> 00:09:57.190
Clearly that's an untenable
position for me to argue.

00:09:57.190 --> 00:10:00.790
But what I would say is, that
smart people can become dumb

00:10:00.790 --> 00:10:03.070
in the sense of being silent.

00:10:03.070 --> 00:10:05.360
And so in a large
enterprise, I would

00:10:05.360 --> 00:10:09.005
submit that silence is the
real enemy of excellence.

00:10:09.005 --> 00:10:10.380
BOB SUTTON: So
just real quickly,

00:10:10.380 --> 00:10:14.010
I was at Pixar yesterday and met
with some of the senior folks.

00:10:14.010 --> 00:10:17.587
And one thing that they
did-- because Pixar

00:10:17.587 --> 00:10:19.170
is sort of at this
point in transition

00:10:19.170 --> 00:10:21.130
where they've kind of grown
up and everything-- and so

00:10:21.130 --> 00:10:22.713
Ed Catmull, who is
president of Pixar,

00:10:22.713 --> 00:10:25.130
was worried that too many
people were being silent.

00:10:25.130 --> 00:10:27.835
And the way Pixar actually
does movies is that, four

00:10:27.835 --> 00:10:33.610
or five people who are the brain
trust-- John Lasseter, Pete

00:10:33.610 --> 00:10:36.650
Docter, a number of other folks,
who make comments on movies,

00:10:36.650 --> 00:10:37.670
and they write notes.

00:10:37.670 --> 00:10:39.850
But they had notes
days where everybody

00:10:39.850 --> 00:10:41.280
wrote notes about
everything that

00:10:41.280 --> 00:10:42.860
could be improved at Pixar.

00:10:42.860 --> 00:10:45.100
And it was because they
were worried they had grown

00:10:45.100 --> 00:10:47.844
and the silence had
sort of sunk in.

00:10:47.844 --> 00:10:49.510
And as they had gotten
larger and older,

00:10:49.510 --> 00:10:50.634
there was too much of that.

00:10:50.634 --> 00:10:54.010
And that was a
countervailing force.

00:10:54.010 --> 00:10:55.630
MALE SPEAKER: The
