00:53:08.620 --> 00:53:10.660
other things that they could do?

00:53:10.660 --> 00:53:13.320
And this is a question that
we and the people up scheme

00:53:13.320 --> 00:53:15.020
get asked all the time.

00:53:15.020 --> 00:53:18.260
So since we have you, we can
ask the same question of you.

00:53:18.260 --> 00:53:20.580
And by the way, don't
make it too compelling

00:53:20.580 --> 00:53:22.730
because we want these
people to stay here.

00:53:22.730 --> 00:53:25.386
HUGGY RAO: So Bob why
don't you actually be--

00:53:25.386 --> 00:53:27.760
BOB SUTTON: I don't teach in
a business school, remember.

00:53:27.760 --> 00:53:29.670
I'm an engineering
professor, so therefore, I

00:53:29.670 --> 00:53:31.420
am free to be cynical.

00:53:31.420 --> 00:53:33.780
Our friend Jeff
Pfeffer would tell you

00:53:33.780 --> 00:53:37.040
that, if you're interested
actually in lifetime income,

00:53:37.040 --> 00:53:40.269
that you should only go to a top
eight-- in addition to the fact

00:53:40.269 --> 00:53:42.810
that it's a great vacation, and
all sorts of wonderful things

00:53:42.810 --> 00:53:44.550
happen in business school.

00:53:44.550 --> 00:53:48.251
But you should only go to a top
eight or ten business school.

00:53:48.251 --> 00:53:49.626
Because other than
that it's just

00:53:49.626 --> 00:53:50.830
going to take two
years of your life

00:53:50.830 --> 00:53:52.720
and lower your lifetime income,
and there's very good evidence

00:53:52.720 --> 00:53:53.850
to support this.

00:53:53.850 --> 00:53:57.704
So I want to play the,
sort of, Jeff Pfeffer card.

00:53:57.704 --> 00:53:59.870
But one thing I will say
about the Stanford Business

00:53:59.870 --> 00:54:02.640
School, where I don't
teach, because I'm

00:54:02.640 --> 00:54:06.310
a tenured engineering professor,
is that-- as my understanding--

00:54:06.310 --> 00:54:07.847
is that if you go
to Stanford, it's

00:54:07.847 --> 00:54:09.430
actually a really
good financial deal.

00:54:09.430 --> 00:54:12.070
That on average, you're going
to come out ahead financially.

00:54:12.070 --> 00:54:14.836
And culturally, that's
sort of up to you.

00:54:14.836 --> 00:54:16.710
The final thing I would
say though, since I'm

00:54:16.710 --> 00:54:18.710
from an engineering school
and I'm not engineer,

00:54:18.710 --> 00:54:20.530
is we all know that
the characteristic

00:54:20.530 --> 00:54:23.900
of the current boom is
it's much, much less

00:54:23.900 --> 00:54:27.296
MBA-centric, and
much, much-- you

00:54:27.296 --> 00:54:28.870
know this much
better than I do--

00:54:28.870 --> 00:54:31.310
and much, much more
engineering-centric.

00:54:31.310 --> 00:54:33.660
So it's the engineers'
days, and we're

00:54:33.660 --> 00:54:35.227
winning, even on an engineer.

00:54:35.227 --> 00:54:37.910
HUGGY RAO: So one other
thing to keep in mind

00:54:37.910 --> 00:54:43.200
is, business schools are
changing dramatically too,

00:54:43.200 --> 00:54:46.200
so you don't think of the
MBA as a standalone degree.

00:54:46.200 --> 00:54:48.960
In fact, we have a number of
