00:54:48.960 --> 00:54:51.120
have an MBA, you can
also get a masters

00:54:51.120 --> 00:54:53.170
in computer science and
electrical engineering,

00:54:53.170 --> 00:54:56.170
just to name a few.

00:54:56.170 --> 00:54:59.090
So there are lots of
options and combinations.

00:54:59.090 --> 00:55:02.240
Our experience certainly at
the Stanford Business School

00:55:02.240 --> 00:55:06.110
is, pretty much, the kinds
of people who actually come,

00:55:06.110 --> 00:55:10.450
they're overwhelmingly tilted
towards a startup option.

00:55:10.450 --> 00:55:14.230
By the end of year one, they've
already figured out an idea.

00:55:14.230 --> 00:55:15.410
They're working.

00:55:15.410 --> 00:55:17.020
They're trying to do things.

00:55:17.020 --> 00:55:19.620
And as a matter of fact,
right before I came here,

00:55:19.620 --> 00:55:23.740
I was actually teaching a course
along with a finance professor

00:55:23.740 --> 00:55:26.725
and a marketing professor,
a course called "From Launch

00:55:26.725 --> 00:55:28.140
to Liquidity."

00:55:28.140 --> 00:55:30.580
Once you start a venture,
how do you actually

00:55:30.580 --> 00:55:31.930
think of your exit?

00:55:31.930 --> 00:55:34.370
And I can certainly
tell you, our students

00:55:34.370 --> 00:55:36.870
believe in very liquid futures.

00:55:36.870 --> 00:55:38.670
or at least, they kind
of anticipate that.

00:55:38.670 --> 00:55:39.690
BOB SUTTON: See,
I don't even know

00:55:39.690 --> 00:55:41.410
